spanGrp.span: "Rotten Meat"; transcribed by ER in September 2008; last revision 18.02.2009; still many unclear records, revised for DoBeS project bz WI in Feb 2013
ǂxoaa ng [tya] tya ʘoe he ǂqxʼoaka,
praat van daardie vleis wat vrot is
translation by E: 'ja, praat van daardie stinkvleis'
E says /ʘoe he ǂqxʼoaka/ and /ʘoe ni ǂqxʼoaka/ are both OK, it means the same
that thing (= some person) comes from this side?, I don't know (if) this is a kaffer/black person or ...
tya gao hoo ng ǀxaa ng ǁu ǁxaea ng ǀʼuu xae of,
die ding ('n mens) kom van hierdie kant af, ek weet nie is dit 'n kafer nie af ...
check again together with next record; sound different, but might be OK nevertheless
/gao/ refers to a person here; is often used like this in other texts as well

the /ng/ is definitely there as a particle before /ǀʼuu/ (not just phonetic); not sure whether this is the OBL or something else (but it can't be the COP, since it comes before /ǀʼuu/); might be OBL, check if /ǁxaea/ is often used with /ng/ if the complement is a clause?!
check again together with preceding record
/tyuu xae ng ku/ = 'wie is hy', but end is hard to understand
he has such a brown colour, a brown person
kua ki so ʼn bruin kleur, so ʼn bruiner,
hy het so 'n bruin kleur, so 'n bruiner
both C and E translate and repeat this record identical, so I believe it, even if it sounds very different to me
C says it is /ku saa/ 'he comes', I hear /au saa/ or /uu saa/ or /u saa/, I think she first said 'toe gee ek hom'?; E also says /ku saa/, might be OK
"ek ou vir julle van dié vleis"
a more literal translation could be: 'I give you (from) this meat'
OK, checked with E and C
checked with E and C; OK
"if you want to cook it, you cook it, if you don't want to cook it, you just roast it"
"a si ǃoon ǂaoa a ǃxama ki, a hu ǃxama ki, ǃoon ǁu ǂaoa a ǃxama ki, a ke maar ǃʼhau ki",
"as jy hom wil kook, toe kook jy hom, as jy wil nie kook nie, daar maar braai jy hom"
[ke a]: might be /ke/ only; check again
"ah, my brother, I will just roast it"
"a ng ǁaun, na si maar ǃʼhau ki",
"a, my broer, ek sal hom maar braai"
the [ng] is probably phonetically only; not repeated by E and C
C translates as 1SG, to me it sound like /ha/; check again (makes also sense in the context)

this plus following records was translated as '(ek) sny hom af nogal die heupbeen'; E is also not sure about the beginning; she guesses /na ǀaa na ../ 'ek vat vir my.../ (2009: could that be /ǀii-a/ with -a being the BEN?!; or is it just 'cut'?!)
chek again; C translates as 'cut' again, so I believe it
C says she should say /ǀaa ǁhau-a/ 'cut off', but she says just 'ǀaa(-ʼa?) 'cut'; the /'a/ might be the verb suffix
E says it is /ǀaa na/ 'vat vir my'
the same wih both E and C

could be [gǃai kiin ǀʼii], or [gǃai kiin ng ǀʼii]or [gǃai ki ng ǀʼii]? then [ǃgai] is maybe NOT to be the same as [gǃao]? could it be a vtr vs. vitr verb?; but here it is translated as 'gooi op' ('put on'?) by C; strange at the moment; E says this is probably '... braai [hom] op die vuur' /ng ǃhau ki ng ǀʼii/, I would prefer /gǃai kiin ǀʼii/
in repetition 'fire' was sometimes [ǀʼii], sometimes [ǀʼai] (never heard [ǀʼai] before!; should the form be added into the dictionary?)
C says, coals would be better than fire here, because you put the meat on hot coals to roast it

first translated as 'ek het gesien', then also as 'ek sien', (then as 'hy sien, hy het gesien', but this is probably a misunderstanding/mispronunciation); might be interessting for verb stem variation /nǀaa/ vs. /nǀii/
that things (= worms) boil out at the other side
gunn ngke ǀuun ǁʼang ng ki ǁʼannʼa ng ki ǁʼannʼa,

/ngke/ does not sound like [ngke]; check again; a few words in the middle are missing; checked with E, she has the same as C and is quite sure about it; the end sounds different, but it is ignored by both C and E
[C is not really sure what this has to do with the rest of the story; E says this refers to the worm that come out of the meat while it is roasted; makes sense to me]
kook anderkant uit = oorkook = überkochen; AFR 'goed' = PL 'things, goods', so PL translation is OK
/gunn ngke/ sounds like [gunnuka], bur both C and E seem to be sure that this is /gunn ngke/
E repeates exactly the same (only) with an inserted [ni], which is prob. not there; she thinks this refers to the worms that come out of the meat
not sure if the first OBL is really there; E says /ǁʼanna/ means 'daardie kant' (or: 'soentoe'); it cannot be combined with 'sit', then you must say ?
E repeats /ka ǃʼuun/, not /kan ǃʼhunn/; might be the phonetic [ng] again
E: /ka ǃʼhuun/ = 'worms'; /ǃʼhuunsi/ = 'worm'; *ka ǃʼhuunsi => ungrammatical; but see rec. 024
I just make this with them, I like meat
ng neti ng kxʼuu ng nǁngke, ng tsʼaanʼa ʘoe,
ek maak net soo vir hulle, (want) ek hou van vleis
I hear something like [tsʼinn] before /tsʼaan/, but it was not repeated by E
in repetition, the /ng/ 'OBL' before /nǁngke/ is clearly there!; C confirms that /nǁngke/ is 'hulle'; E confirms also /nǁng-ke/ is 'hulle' here, and she also repeats the OBL before it
another version: /na heen ng kxʼuu ng nǁng-ke/ (Sven says, he knows this /heen/ from A)

when asked for it, E says, /ng knnke/, /ng kike/, /ng knn/ are all OK with OBL, but it was not convincing; she says /ng hng/ is also OK, and she adds that her father spoke like this (somewhere else she says, her father spoke almost like Andries)
'tog te oor ...' = 'to like something; to be mad about s.th.'; I cant't find it in any dictionary, but I checked it with an Afrikaans speaker
to me, it sounds like /ng ng ǀii/, C repeats as /ng ǀii/ or /na ng ǀii/; check; the /na/ might be prompted by my wrong repetition; might then be /nou ng ǀii/; or maybe C wanted to say /a ng ǀii/
does not sound like /nǀii/, but C and E repeat and translate it identically; I believe it

interessting; C translates as /hom/, the rec. before is also 'one worm', but she uses hngke here; later translated as 'hulle'; number is a strange category in Nǀuu!? E repeats first 'hulle' [dyeke] (= /ki-ke/), then /hngke/ or [ngke?] here, but SG in the preceding rec.!
E confirms that this is /na nǀii/
structure not clear to me, check elicitations (NC071107-01_A.&007); E repeats [knn ke a dyeke] or [... tyike], or [... kyike]; the original recording here sounds more like [kike]
I see again, here they are
ng gǀoe nǀii, knn ke kike,
toe sien ek weer hier is hulle
this is probably the same as rec. 024 + 025 and elicitation in NC071107-01_A.&007
I see again, here they are
ng gǀoe nǀii knn a kike,
toe sien ek weer hier is hulle
/kike/ sounds like [kidyeke], C says she just stutters a little bit
2009: probably better translated as 'to sien ek weer, hier is hulle'

the second part was repeated as /ǁhuu/ 'ek byt af by C', but it sounds very different; more like [ǁʼnn]; check again; E also repeats /tsʼii ǁhuu/ and confirms that the last word is the same as in /ka ǃaqa ǁhau/
no relative marker here? check 080812C; E confirmed that no REL marker is necessary here
sounds like [maar he]; check if 'be rotten' and 'stink' is exactly the same, E says it is the same word
but it is rotten or: stinks; it is a rotten thing
maar hy is vrot; dis 'n vrotsel
check if 'be rotten' and 'stink' is exactly the same; probably yes (E); alternative translation: 'but it stinks'
C says it is /ha/, it sounds like /hulle/; E also repeats just /ha/
E's version: 'hy [die vleis] smaak na worms' = /tsʼinn ka ǃʼhuun/
[kan] probably /ka (ng) ǃʼhuun/ again, with phonetical nasal due to delayed aspirated click
C whispers, she can't understand herself what she said here; E also does not understand; could be /ng gǀoe nǀii/, but that's my guess only
E gives /oh, ka ǃʼhuun ke ngke/; 'oh, hier is worms'; check again! hard to hear; 2009: but probably OK
the /-ke/ might also be the COP/FOC instead of the PL-suffix
C ignores the beginning; might be /gǀoe/ 'again'; yes, confirmed by E
E says 'food' is [aanki], and 'eat it' is [ain ki]; might be true, at least for the Upington speakers
first translated by C as 'ek gaan uit' /nǀng ǁʼnn/ (without the context of the following record); then, together with following rec.: toe loop byt ek (aan) die been
E 'ek eet so lat ek (later) die been loop byt' (together with preceding and next record); E: lat (so dat) ek loop en ...
C says the verb is loop (uit)
tya kama ng xa mos (...) ǁai, a ǁai nou tyoa, a ng ke nou tsʼii
check again with C, end might be completely wrong!
C: 'die tyd wat ek gekom het, die been(e) is nou op, toet is daardie goed op (???)', E does not understand
C: /a ng ke nou tsʼii/? sounds like /knna i tsʼii/, but C also might be right?!
C confirms that /aan habu/ and /aan tyoa/ is the same, both mean 'eat up' (C: /ng aan habu(-a)/tyoa(-a) ainki/) (-a = past)
angeblich soll gehen: /ng aan aanki tyoaa/!; nice elicitation with E siehe 080820E...
ng tsʼaku ǁu ǂʼiin, na ka ng (...) ǁqxʼaan si siinsnn,
toe dink ek my maag sal werk
ek het nie gedink my maag kan werk nie
E: /ng tsʼaaku ǁu ǂʼain ng ǁqxʼaan si siinsinn/ 'ek het seker nie gedink my maag sal werk nie'
2009: does /ǂain/ normally appear as /ǂainka/? check (cf. ); looks like this, at least frequently; is this /ǂain-a-ka/? cf. past translation in notes; would be an interessting suffix order then
maar ng ǁqxʼaan ke ǁam xng [ǁam xng]
maar my maag, hy het nie ...
what is /ku/? same construction as /ng ǁu si (ku ng) X/ 'I will not X'?
I am full of the meat
ek is vol van die vleis
I first had the OBL here? before /ʘoe/, but I don't hear anything! E repeats it; check again
but now, yes, the other worms
maar nou ja kaǃʼhuun ng koke
maar nou, ja, die ander wurms
I shook off the other worms
xng kaǃaqa ǁhau kaǃʼhuun ng koke
ek het die ander wurms uitgeskud
E: /ni nǀii ki/?; C: /ng neti nǀii ki/; does not sound like this!
do you think I throw it away? I ...
gǀa ǂʼiinka, ng ǂaqbe ǁʼae ki, ng
dink jy ek (sal) hom weggooi? ek ...
C repeats with /ng si/ 'ek sal'; I don't hear the /si/; /ki/ also sound a little bit different to me
[ǂaqbe ǁʼae] and [ǂaqbe ǁʼaa] seem to be the same; C uses them interchangeably
just shake (the worms) off, then I ...
ek skud net uit, toe ek ...
C does not understand herself; E does also not understand
my guess: /a nau tsʼii ǁhuu/ 'I bite off'?!
tot daardie vleis (loop) opgeraak (het)/ tot die vleis op is
'until the meat it eaten up completely'
C later repeats ǁʼae as ǁʼng; and [toet] is in repetitition clearly just 'tot' 'until'
when? the meat is now finished ...
"when the meat is (eaten) up, (then)...' => nǁaka? check with Lenas examples
/nǁaka/ is 'daardie' according to C, not convinced, I think it is 'when, as'
E says /nǁaka/ means 'as' or 'toe', so it really might be 'when'; she also gave /... ha tyoa/ but I rather hear /nou tyoa/; cf. also next record, there is a now there
/ǀxuru/ 'juice, soup' is used here for the ''marrow" of the bone [dt. 'Knochenmark']
/hngke/ refers to the 'juice'; I often have PL pronouns refering to /aanki/ 'food', /ǃqhaa/ 'water' etc.
no, heavens, Ou Sus, you were greedy
nee, jene Ou Sus, a xa ǀqurua,
nee, Ou Sus, jy was snoep
E gave /..., Ou Sus, maar a ǀqurua/ 'maar jy is snoep', but to me it is /a xa ǀqurua/ instead
/ǂʼainka/ or /ǂʼainke/? E repeats first /-ke/!; then /-ka/; sounds like /-ka/ here, but it sounded like /-ke/ in an earlier record; check again
I think my stomach will ache, (but) no
ng nǁae ǂʼiinka, ng nǁann si tsʼii, haʼa
dink ek my maag sal pyn, haʼa
ǂʼain and ǂʼainka is the same acc. to E
the expression 'my liver bites' is used in Nǀuu for 'my stomach aches'
nee, [gao] a ǂxoa gao he ǂʼiin,
nee, jy praat 'n ding wat kort is
E stellt fest, dass die Geschichte nur sehr kurz war; sound like /no, gao ..., nou? ǂxoa (ng) ke mos e he ǂʼain/; check again
yes, I just told you it is just a short story (lit.: small piece)
ja, na (mos) kua ng gǀa (ki), ki net so ʼn klein stukkie,
ja, ek het mos vir jou gesê dis net so 'n klein stukkie
I get the thought of the worms that I ate already?
na hoo tya gedagte ng ka ǃʼhuun he xa al aan
ek kry daardie gedagte van die wurms wat ek al geëet het
/he/ (instead of /ni/) as REL because 'worms' are OBJ of relative clause or X clause? (cf. Collins grammar sketch)
I would take it, I (would) give (it) to the dog
[na ...] si ǀii ki, ng aa ǂhunna,
ek sal hom vat en vir die hond gee
beginning sounds different, hard to hear; E says it is probably wrong
but at that time, I ate it
maar daai tyd, ng xa aana ki,
maar daardie tyd, ek het hom geëet
aana [ha] tya ʘoe, ng ng ain,
E is very unsure about this; ask C
?until I have eaten up the meat
toet ek die vleis klaar geëet het
nicht klar ob sich das toet auf den vorigen oder den nachfolgenden rec. bezieht; check!!!
go and dig them(selves) in there; you know what meat looks like ...?
ǁʼng ǁʼau ǀʼee hngke ng ki nǁaa, a ke mos ǁxaea ʘoe (hi a),
loop grou hulle (die worms) daar in, jy weet mos hoe lyk vleis
E says /a(a)/ is 'like' and [hi] might be 'how' cf. elicitation and comments under NC071107-01_A.&005
E repeated /ǁʼaa ǁʼaa/, to me it sounds like /ǁʼng ǁʼaa/, but both would not be surprising
same translation from bith E and C, so it's probably correct
they dig, (they) go and make a small cavity
hng ǁʼau, ǁʼaa kxʼuu kamersi ʘuun,
hulle grou, toe loop maak (hulle) 'n kamertjie
E says it is /ǁʼng kxʼuu/, I hear [ǁʼaa kxʼuu]!
the worms dig themselves into the bones
no, I scrape them out from there
nee, ng ǁxao ǁhuu kike ng tyoxoe,
nee, toe krap ek hulle daar uit
C repeats /tya guuke/ insetad of /kike/, E repeats [dyeke], or [tyike] again
I throw (them) away, I bite off from that meat
ng ǂaqbe ǁʼaa, ng tsʼii ǁhuu ng tya ʘoe,
ek gooi hulle weg, en ek byt af van die vleis
check if there is really an OBL here; E repeats it, I don't really hear it; 2009: it seems to be there indeed
no, Ou Sus (you) did really, I would not eat like you
nee Ou Sus ke xa rêrig, ng ǁu si aan (...) ǁaa a,
nee, Ou Sus het rêrig, ek sal nie eet soos jy nie
maar die saam wat ek nie sien nie
ek byt af, daar sommer ek ...
once again, C has /nǀa/ followed by OBL
